“Ever since Nora, the heroine of Henrik Ibsen’s proto-feminist masterwork “A Doll’s House,” from 1879, walked out on her husband and out of her domestic cage, actresses have yearned to play her. Jessica Chastain (above, center), last year’s Best Actress Oscar winner, steps into the role for a sixteen-week Broadway run, now in previews at the Hudson, opening March 9. Jamie Lloyd directs a new adaptation, by Amy Herzog, featuring (from left to right) Arian Moayed (“Succession”) and Okieriete Onaodowan (“Hamilton”).” 

-The New Yorker

20 Electric Years

What an absolute thrill to celebrate 20 electric years of Waterwell shows and education programs. Tom Ridgely and I always dreamed that we would be able to build a community of like minded citizens that believed theater is a tool to better society. @waterwelltheater continues to be a home for those change-makers and innovative artists and I couldn’t be prouder. 

Join our celebration.

While Raisi was lying inside of @unitednations headquarters, Iranians gathered outside to make sure world leaders hear the truth: the Iranian people want this murderous regime gone. @arianmoayed joined @womanlifefreedomnyc for a powerful speech:

“We cannot wait for the governments to do it. We cannot wait for one Savior to do it, or two saviors. It has to be ALL OF US, together. 

Tell the stories of your family... tell the stories of the people that are fighting on the ground right now. 

Now is not a time for cowardice. Now is a time for hope and bravery... ZAN ZENDEGI AZADI!”

🎥: @eyesofnima 
📷: @parsagarrett

The Old Young Crow, executive produced by me, Rayka Zehtabchi and Scott Aharoni, has won almost 40 awards worldwide after being selected by over 110 film festivals, 15 of those being Academy Award Qualifying. 

Directed, Written, Produced, Edited, Animated, and Illustrated by Liam LoPinto, The Old Young Crow tells the story of Mehrdad, an Iranian boy who befriends an old Japanese woman at a graveyard in Tokyo. It’s a hybrid of live-action and animation techniques punctuated by Liam’s grandfather and Googoosh’s phenomenal hit, Hejrat. 

It’s currently available for view in the Academy Screening Room: For Your Consideration for Best Live-Action Short.

I woke up this morning thinking about my dear friends, who I miss deeply and who happened to also be great artists. @succession

The fourth and final panel of our leadership retreat was moderated by Dr. Hamid Biglari who asked penetrating questions of @raminbahrani, an Academy Award, BAFTA, WGA, and Emmy-nominee, @arianmoayed, the Co-Founder of Waterwell and an Emmy and Tony-nominee actor, @shirin__neshat, a world-renowned multi-disciplinary artist and filmmaker, and @sanaztss, a Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright.

Each of them discussed the role that activism has – or has not – played in their art and how their own views as well as external views of their Iranian American identities have affected their creative works.

#IALeaders #IAArtists

From Utah Shakes to Fever Chart to Food & Fadwa to Abe and to  @Waterwell’s A GOOD DAY TO ME NOT TO YOU, Lameece always penetrates your heart so deeply that you learn more about yourself. She happens to also be one of my favorite human beings. 

With RAVE reviews from NY Times and New Yorker, Lee Sunday Evans has directed a masterful piece of theater that moves audience to laughter and tears. 

A whole community of people from Rachel Sussman + Diana DiMenna to the team at Waterwell have come together to tell this deeply resonate and powerful story that Lameece has written and performs every night.

There are only two weeks left and I just hope you can do whatever you can to see this monumental and cathartic show now playing at the Connelly Theater.
